<subSubSection id="D87AD5C8363A0E518F0DA4EC123F0386" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="1934B0A293A3E54A1C591864915D7332" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5989D2E845482A1DB715AC6C4B623C8E" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="2FFDCDCAE546E7FEB42919C8EADF9779" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">in Japan.</emphasis>
Nansei Islands, Ogasawara Islands, Volcano Island. Northern limit lies in Kodakara-jima of the Tokara Islands (
<bibRefCitation id="25B2771139D749422FABC10F4DB1C7C1" author="Yamane, Sk" journalOrPublisher="Asakura-shoten, Tokyo" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" refId="B16" refString="Yamane, Sk, Fukumoto, S, 2017. Chapter 6. Tramp ant species in the Satsunan Islands, 108-131. In: Kagoshima University Biodiversity Study Group (Ed.) Alien Animals and Plants in the Amami Islands. Nanpo-shinsha, Kagoshima. [In Japanese]" title="Chapter 6. Tramp ant species in the Satsunan Islands, 108 - 131. In: Kagoshima University Biodiversity Study Group (Ed.) Alien Animals and Plants in the Amami Islands. Nanpo-shinsha, Kagoshima. [In Japanese]" year="2017">Yamane and Fukumoto 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68C31E5D9BF4063AFB7F8B525797AB87" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="454A9042EE47E12D99210FCC4E4F771A" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="98EA703D46377534A50AD5D1E4C22F3E" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">
<taxonomicName id="31E4D73DD1B4EF6DB8D41AAC9D6F3AF3" baseAuthorityName="F. Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetramorium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Tetramorium simillimum" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simillimum">
<emphasis id="63DED0D00A3AC616BD608C548FE7DF0F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">Tetramorium simillimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="77832392B766F9388489AB641C1047F9" class="Insecta" genus="T." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="T. simillimum" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simillimum">
<emphasis id="6678A738444A3931396CD621F7B4B4CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="43">T. simillimum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<bibRefCitation id="354FA387DCE810E823DC917505AECEC4" author="Bolton, B" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="67 - 151" refId="B5" refString="Bolton, B, 1977. The ant tribe Tetramoriini (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). The genus Tetramorium Mayr in the Oriental and Indo-Australian regions, and in Australia. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology Series 36: 67 - 151" title="The ant tribe Tetramoriini (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). The genus Tetramorium Mayr in the Oriental and Indo-Australian regions, and in Australia." volume="36" year="1977">Bolton 1977</bibRefCitation>
). In the queen, it is easily distinguished from other Japanese congeners by the following character conditions: i) dorsum of head with regular longitudinal striae, with interspaces densely sculptured and mat; ii) erect body hairs not sharply pointed apically; iii) petiole anteriorly truncate, with dorsal face clearly separated from anterior slope with sharp angle; iv) basal 1/3 of gastral tergite 1 micropunctate or coriaceous and mat (sometimes weakly shiny). This species is a famous tramp of African origin (
<bibRefCitation id="71C1DCBB0A271A6031A0DA18CC6B734C" author="Bolton, B" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology Series" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" pagination="67 - 151" refId="B5" refString="Bolton, B, 1977. The ant tribe Tetramoriini (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). The genus Tetramorium Mayr in the Oriental and Indo-Australian regions, and in Australia. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology Series 36: 67 - 151" title="The ant tribe Tetramoriini (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). The genus Tetramorium Mayr in the Oriental and Indo-Australian regions, and in Australia." volume="36" year="1977">Bolton 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="C9890FA45C40548E1C4694F9BD1C175E" author="Yoshimura, M" journalOrPublisher="Japanese Journal of Entomology (New Series)" pageId="0" pageNumber="43" refId="B18" refString="Yoshimura, M, 2020. Chapter 4. Taxonomy of alien ants, 34-50. In: Hashimoto Y. (Ed.) Gairaiari no Hanashi. Asakura Shoten, Tokyo. [In Japanese]" title="Chapter 4. Taxonomy of alien ants, 34 - 50. In: Hashimoto Y. (Ed.) Gairaiari no Hanashi. Asakura Shoten, Tokyo. [In Japanese]" year="2020">Yoshimura 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
